Tags.string 'NodeComment':
Control Rig is used for an additive slope warp that takes the incoming pose and blends into an FBIK to alligne the feet with the surface. 
We also get the InteractionWorldLocation and the press-button animation has a curve we use to blend into that using also the FBIK so the bot moves his finger to the button location.
Now we get our controls for each feet and use the calcutlated offset and normal rotation and add that to the incoming pose with the FBIK solver.
The curve value is used in the press-button animation to decide when and how much we blend into the interaction world location
We use this to "stabilize" the character as we pull on the other finger.
First we take the foot bone transform and move our IK controls there
Move the Index finger control to the interaction world location also setting the rotation to that from the index finger.
Correct the hip so the legs dont overbend
Use a function to trace and calculate the Z Offset for both feet. Also get the hit normal to rotate the feed later. Check the function for details. Only when not in air.
Get the transform of the control which we placed where the foot bone is. Trace and get the Z component of the hit. Also get the hit normal.

Interp the result to smooth the blend. 
You can have different speeds when blending in our out
With an aim math with Z up we can get the rotation our feed needs to have to stand on the surface.
